Symptoms:
- VPN connects but can't access services
- Can ping VPN server but nothing else on network
- VPN disconnects randomly
- “No data received” in WireGuard stats

Diagnosis:
# On VPN server:
sudo wg show
cat /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward
sudo iptables -t nat -L POSTROUTING

# From client (when connected):
ping 10.0.0.1 # VPN server IP
ping 192.168.1.11 # Homelab VM

Common Causes:
- IP forwarding disabled on VPN server
- Missing MASQUERADE rule
- Firewall blocking traffic
- Client routing not configured
- VPN interface not started on boot

Solutions:

Enable IP forwarding (permanent):
ssh [user]@[vpn-server]
echo “net.ipv4.ip_forward=1” | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.conf
sudo sysctl -p

Add MASQUERADE rule:
sudo iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o ens18 -j MASQUERADE
sudo netfilter-persistent save

Ensure WireGuard starts on boot:
sudo systemctl enable wg-quick@wg0
sudo systemctl start wg-quick@wg0

Allow WireGuard through firewall:
sudo ufw allow 51820/udp # Ubuntu
# or
sudo firewall-cmd –permanent –add-port=51820/udp # Rocky
sudo firewall-cmd –reload

Test from client:
# When VPN connected:
ping 192.168.1.11
# Should work

Prevention:
- Enable WireGuard on boot (systemctl enable)
- Document all VPN firewall rules
- Test VPN after every server reboot
- Keep WireGuard configs in version control
